Introduction¶

In this project, main goal is to predict hourly solar power predictions of KIVANC 2 GES (a solar power plant in Mersin) starting from May 25 to June 3, 2022. Past hourly production data ranging from February 1, 2021 to two days before the current date are provided and updated each day. Thus, prediction is made in a very similar setting to the real life dynamics of energy markets. On day d, production up until day d-2 are given, and prediction is provided for day d+1.¶

In addition to the production data, weather information is provided for 9 different locations. These locations constitute adjacent grid points around the plant and their coordinates range from 36.25 latitude, 33 longtitude to 36.75 latitude, 33.5 longtitude.¶

For each grid point, past hourly observations of four different weather variables are provided. These variables are;¶

TEMP:¶

Temperature at the provided location.¶

REL_HUMIDITY:¶

Relative humidity at the provided location. Gives information about rainy or cloudy weather.¶

DSWRF:¶

Stands for downward shortwave radiation flux. An estimate of the total amount of shortwave radiation (both direct and diffuse) that reaches the Earth's surface.¶

CLOUD_LOW_LAYER:¶

Total cloud cover data for low-level type of clouds.¶

Our starting point is to merge the weather and production data after format corrections. After then, we will construct time series regressive models on the past productions to predict future productions.¶

Locations and weather variables¶

Weather information of 9 different grid points does not present practical information since, when used distinctly, locations cover huge areas compared to the plant's size, and information such as cloudiness, temperature, or dwrf are highly correlated with one another at this level. Thus, instead of continuing with 9 locations, averages of each variable are computed for further investigation.¶

dt[, RELH := rowMeans(dt[,22:30], na.rm=TRUE)]
dt[, TEMP := rowMeans(dt[,31:39], na.rm=TRUE)]
dt[, 4:39 := NULL]

Production Capacities¶

One could easily observe that max production for each month tends to increase up until June 2021. This could result from the progressive increase in the capacity of the power plant. After June, capacity is not changed for a while, and it is pulled down at the beginning of 2022. We will ignore the timeline in which capacities are increased; instead, data from June 2021 will be used for convenience.¶

Daily seasonality for the production data is easily observed. Production volume at hour h in the last day and production at hour h in the previous days are correlated. Therefore, the effects of each variable might differ considerably for different production hours. Our approach here is to divide the production data into 24 hours and make predictions for each hourly data for the next day. Thus, at the end, there will be 24 different models at best, given that there are distinct models for each hour. However, further examination is required before any action towards modeling is taken.¶

Cutting thresholds for weather variables¶

By analyzing the ggpair plot, it is observed that production and weather data are not strictly correlated in a linear fashion. Instead there are certain thresholds before/after practical patterns are to be observed. We will use additional variables in order to explain these behaviours. DSWRF variable seems to maximize the production after its numerical value pass 300, thus a variable named DSWRF_above is introduced. Further, temperature maximizes the production after its numerical value pass 302. TEMP_above is introduced at this point. In a similar manner, RELH_above and CLL_above are introduced as well.¶

We had tried using dummy variables, but they didn't catch the difference from border points, so we used additional variables instead of dummy variables.¶

In [14]:
dt[, DSWRF_above := ifelse(DSWRF > 300, DSWRF, 0)]

dt[, TEMP_above := ifelse(TEMP > 302, TEMP, 0)]

dt[, RELH_above := ifelse(RELH > 75, RELH, 0)]

dt[, CLL_above := ifelse(CLL > 40, CLL, 0)]

For each weather variable, lagged values for hours h-1, h-2, h-3, h-4, h-5, and future productions for hours h+1, h+2, and h+3 are used. These might be explanatory since weather events tend to have cumulative effects. In addition, rolling mean of CLL variable is added to improve the stability.¶

Maximum productions¶

One could suggest that there will be no solar energy production at night hours and, therefore, there is no need to construct models for such hours. To support this claim, hourly maximum productions are printed. It is observed that, in fact, there are no productions between 9 pm and 5 am. We can simply predict 0 KW as the hourly production for such hours. In addition to these hours, maximum hourly production at 8 pm seems pretty low. In order to observe the production distribution, a table of production hours is constructed. Here, there is only one day in which production exceeded 0 KW. Simply ignoring this, we have 8 pm to 5 am as the fixed predictions of 0 KW production.¶

As was observed in the production plots, the plant operates by changing its capacity throughout the seasons. In order to use production volumes of different date times when capacities are non-constant, we will scale the production volumes. The most sensible way to scale these numerical values is to divide them by the capacity of the product at the given time. Capacity determination is another issue here. Our approach to the capacity is to consider the maximum production of a time window of predetermined size as the capacity of the plant within that time window. The Time window size is one month (30 days) for convenience.¶

In addition, the data frame is divided into hours so that distinct models can be constructed for each hour. Here, lagged production volumes (scaled) are introduced as well. lag72 stands for the scaled production three days before, and each 24 hours increment depicts one day lag. lag24 and lag48 cannot be used since prediction for d+1 is made by the past production data up until the end of day d-2.¶

In [17]:
dt_hour <- list()
for (h in 5:19){
    dt_hour[[h]] <- dt[hour == h]
    dt_hour[[h]][, capacity := frollapply(production, 30, FUN="max", align="right", na.rm=T)]
    dt_hour[[h]][, scaledprod := production/capacity]
    dt_hour[[h]][, scaledprod_lag72 := shift(scaledprod, 3)]
    dt_hour[[h]][, scaledprod_lag96 := shift(scaledprod, 4)]
    dt_hour[[h]][, scaledprod_lag120 := shift(scaledprod, 5)]
}

Performance Measure¶

Our models will be tested by the performance measure of WMAPE (weighted mean absolute percentage error). Formula for WMAPE is provided below;¶

$$ \frac{\sum_1^n| Actual - Forecast| }{\sum_1^n| Forecast|} $$

Assumption and Modeling Approach¶

From now on, different linear regression models will be implemented only for the production data at 12 pm. After the selection of most suitable model according to the test results, we will train the whole data and make predictions. Training data will cover the timeline from March 1, 2022 to June 1, 2022 and the rest is for test. Since, prediction will be made for the month June, keeping the past productions would decrease the accuracy of our model. For model selection, R^2 does not give insightful information. Instead, focusing on WMAPE is critical.¶

For the first model, all the variables introduced above are used and WMAPE is computed.¶

Conclusion and Future Work¶

Our final model has a very low WMAPE by the test results, and the model provided a total WMAPE of 0.109 for the competition phase (May 25 to June 23). However, improvements and further corrective actions are possible.

First, instead of fitting a model for 12 pm and choosing the best values, one could construct models for each hour and repeat the improvement steps for these models. This would require much more computational time and effort, yet; might not prove to be worthy at the end for close hours (models for 12 pm, 13 pm and 14 pm would show pretty similar characteristics for instance). Another approach could be dividing the data into several parts consisting of 4 to 6 hours and trying different models for each part, this time model variables are the same for different hours within the same sub-part.

Moreover, these models are constructed such that predictions for June, July and August at most can be made. Cutting a great portion of the dataset would prevent us from predicting future productions in Fall or other seasons. Regardless of the length of the dataset, WMAPE would increase due to increasing variability. However; one could use related portion of the dataset as well. For instance, if we were to make predictions for November 2022, training the data on the Fall of 2021 could prove to be more practical.

Most of the features are removed due to correlations between variables. These kind of prediction making procedures involve high levels of interrelation in terms of attributes and one might anaylze the variables more elaborately for further predictions. Model imperfections result not only from variable relations, but also production data itself. There are no visible patterns, seasonalities or trends for most of the hours.

In conclusion, time series approach to the solar power production is considerably difficult and our model, inevitably, shows weaknesses for some of the hours. However, according to the weather in the plant area, we can provide predictions up until 0.05 weighted mean absolute percentage error and give useful insights.
